Reduced Instruction Set Computer (RISC) architecture improves processor performance by 
simplifying instruction sets, minimizing memory access, and emphasizing register-based 
operations. In RISC systems, computations are primarily performed within processor 
registers using fixed-length instructions and limited addressing modes, enabling faster 
decoding and execution. Techniques such as pipelining further enhance throughput by 
overlapping instruction stages including fetch, decode, and execute. However, the design of 
compact and efficient Arithmetic Logic Units (ALUs) and register files remains critical for 
achieving low-area and low-power processor implementations, particularly in embedded and 
FPGA-based systems. 

This work presents the design and implementation of an 8-bit ALU and Register File using 
Verilog HDL as core components of a mini processor system. The ALU supports a range of 
arithmetic and logical operations, including addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, 
increment, decrement, AND, OR, and XOR, along with accurate generation of status flags 
such as Zero, Carry, and Auxiliary Carry. The register file is designed with multiple general
purpose registers to enable efficient data storage and transfer. The design emphasizes 
deterministic operation through proper initialization, controlled data flow, and reliable 
handling of exceptional conditions such as division by zero. A modular design methodology is 
adopted using standard combinational and sequential building blocks, and functional 
simulation verifies the correctness and robustness of the system. 

For hardware validation, the design is synthesized on a Xilinx xc7a35tcpg236-1 FPGA 
device. The implementation demonstrates compact resource utilization, occupying 208 Look
Up Tables (1.00% of 20,800), 108 Flip-Flops (0.26% of 41,600), 10 I/O pins (9.43% of 106), 
and one global buffer (3.13% of 32). The total on-chip power consumption is measured at 
3.164 W, with a junction temperature of 40.8 °C and a thermal margin of 44.2 °C. Although 
the power estimation confidence is reported as low, the results indicate that the proposed 
design achieves efficient performance with minimal resource overhead. 
The proposed implementation demonstrates a compact, reliable, and scalable processor 
component design, making it suitable for low-cost and low-power embedded system 
applications.
